  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>Somewhere in the bloodstream of a patient enrolled in trial NCT05144386, the CRISPR machinery was still present at 48 weeks. The dual guide RNAs had found their targets. The AAV9 vectors had delivered their payload. The Cas9 nuclease had made its cuts, flanking key segments of integrated HIV proviral DNA and physically excising them from the host genome. By every measurable indicator of the editing event itself, EBT-101 had worked. And then the antiretrovirals stopped — and HIV RNA climbed back.</p>
  <p>This is not a story about a technology that failed. It is a story about a technology that worked precisely well enough to reveal a problem that predates it by decades. The virus did not evade the guide RNAs. It hid from them — tucked inside resting CD4+ T cells and macrophages and hematopoietic progenitors scattered across lymph nodes, gut-associated lymphoid tissue, and the central nervous system, transcriptionally silent, metabolically invisible, waiting. CRISPR cannot edit what it cannot find. That is not a CRISPR limitation. That is the HIV reservoir problem, and it has defeated every cure strategy that has ever confronted it.</p>
  <p>What happened next is the more interesting story. The same platform, the same allogeneic engineering logic, a different disease — and early data that looks nothing like failure.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-reservoir-problem" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Reservoir Problem Nobody Solved Before CRISPR and Nobody Has Solved Since</h2>
  <p>HIV's central evolutionary achievement is not its mutation rate, though that is formidable. It is the provirus. When HIV infects a CD4+ T cell, its RNA genome is reverse-transcribed into DNA and integrated into the host chromosome, where it can persist indefinitely in a latent state. Antiretroviral therapy suppresses viral replication to undetectable levels but cannot touch integrated proviral DNA. Stop the drugs, and the reservoir reactivates. This has been true since the first effective ART regimens in the 1990s, and it remains true now.</p>
  <p>EBT-101's approach — delivering CRISPR-Cas9 via AAV9 vectors to excise proviral DNA directly — is mechanistically sound. A 2019 study published in <em>Nature Communications</em> demonstrated that combining long-acting slow-effective release ART (LASER ART) with AAV9-delivered CRISPR-Cas9 excised 60–80% of integrated HIV DNA across multiple tissues including spleen, lymph nodes, and brain in a subset of humanized mice, with no detectable off-target effects and no viral rebound in virus-eradicated animals. That result, in mice, was striking enough to justify a human trial.</p>
  <p>The human trial produced six participants, no serious adverse events, and four viral rebounds. A 2025 review in <em>Current Opinion in HIV and AIDS</em> identified the core problem plainly: low in vivo editing efficiency remains the central barrier, particularly for proviral excision strategies requiring transfection of all HIV-infected cells. The AAV9 vectors reach some cells. They do not reach all cells. The cells they miss are sufficient to rekindle infection when immune pressure is removed.</p>
  <p>One participant was different. That person showed a delayed rebound of nearly 16 weeks — roughly four months after antiretroviral interruption — and a significant reduction in reservoir size. Rachel Presti, MD, PhD, medical director of the infectious disease clinical research unit at Washington University, St. Louis, described it with the precision of someone who knows exactly how much weight a single data point can bear: "Those exploratory endpoints promise that maybe there was some effect in at least one participant, and we're trying to figure out what was different about that person and how we can continue to make this better."</p>
  <p>That sentence is where the HIV cure story actually lives right now. Not in the four rebounds. In the one outlier, and in the question of whether whatever biological circumstance produced that result can be identified, reproduced, and scaled.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"CRISPR cannot edit what it cannot find. That is not a CRISPR limitation. That is the HIV reservoir problem, and it has defeated every cure strategy that has ever confronted it."</p></aside>

<section id="three-strategies" class="reveal">
  <h2>Three Strategies, Three Sets of Problems</h2>
  <p>The field is pursuing parallel approaches, and each one runs into a different wall. The excise strategy — EBT-101's approach — confronts the reservoir problem directly. The protect strategy attempts to sidestep it by making new immune cells resistant to infection. The attack strategy tries to eliminate infected cells before they can reactivate.</p>
  <p>The protect strategy has its own ceiling. A 2019 paper in the <em>New England Journal of Medicine</em> described transplantation of CRISPR-edited CCR5-ablated hematopoietic stem and progenitor cells into a patient with both HIV and acute lymphocytic leukemia. The cells engrafted for over 19 months with no gene-editing-related adverse events — but CCR5 disruption efficiency was only 5.2–8.28% of transplanted cells. That is nowhere near sufficient to confer protection. The logic of the protect strategy requires that CCR5-negative cells eventually outcompete CCR5-positive cells and dominate the immune repertoire, as happened naturally in the Berlin and London patients cured by allogeneic stem cell transplant from CCR5-Δ32 donors. At 5–8% editing efficiency, that competitive advantage never materializes.</p>
  <p>The 2025 Ragon Institute study, published in <em>Nature Communications</em>, moved that number dramatically. Researchers at MIT, Harvard, and Massachusetts General Hospital edited the CCR5 gene in over 90% of human blood stem cells with minimal or no detectable off-target effects. CCR5-edited mice remained uninfected even after a second HIV exposure at five times the original dose. That is a genuine technical milestone. It is also, for now, a milestone in mice.</p>
  <p>The CCR5 strategy carries a concern that deserves more than a footnote. A published study found that homozygosity for the CCR5-Δ32 mutation — the natural analog of what CRISPR aims to engineer — is associated with reduced life expectancy. The mechanism is not fully characterized, but CCR5 is not merely an HIV co-receptor; it plays roles in immune trafficking and neuroinflammation. Ablating it permanently in hematopoietic stem cells means every immune cell derived from those progenitors will lack CCR5 for the patient's lifetime. The long-term systemic consequences of that are not yet known. Additionally, CCR5 ablation only protects against R5-tropic HIV strains. CXCR4-tropic strains, which become more prevalent in late-stage disease, infect cells independently of CCR5 — and disrupting CXCR4 as an alternative impairs engraftment of stem cells in bone marrow, which is not a trade-off anyone wants to make.</p>
  <p>HIV's mutation rate compounds every strategy. Guide RNAs designed against conserved regions of one HIV subtype may have multiple mismatches against sequences circulating in other patients or other geographies. Chantelle Ahlenstiel, PhD, senior research fellow in immunovirology at the Kirby Institute at UNSW Sydney, has been direct about this: "It will be important to design further gRNA that are highly conserved across all HIV subtypes in order to develop a globally applicable HIV gene therapy." That is a significant design constraint when the virus that circulates in sub-Saharan Africa is not the same virus that circulates in North America or Europe.</p>
</section>

