<section id="the-autoimmune-pivot" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Autoimmune Pivot Is Not a Consolation Prize</h2>
  <p>Here is the counterintuitive part. The biological property that makes CRISPR insufficient for HIV — its inability to reach and edit every relevant cell in the body — turns out to be largely irrelevant in autoimmune disease. Not because the delivery problem is solved, but because the therapeutic goal is different.</p>
  <p>In lupus and systemic sclerosis, the pathological actors are autoreactive B cells — cells that have escaped tolerance checkpoints and are producing antibodies against the body's own tissues. The hypothesis underlying CRISPR CAR-T therapy in these conditions is not that you need to permanently eliminate every autoreactive B cell. It is that you need to deplete the B-cell compartment transiently and completely enough that when it reconstitutes from naive precursors, the autoreactive clones do not return. The immune system reboots. The pathological memory is erased.</p>
  <p>This is the hit-and-run strategy, and it may be the optimal design rather than a compromise. Katy Rezvani, head of the Institute for Cell Therapy Discovery and Innovation at MD Anderson, has described the mechanism directly: "CAR T therapies have already demonstrated remarkable success in conditions like lupus and systemic sclerosis by selectively depleting autoreactive B cells, resulting in sustained immune reset." The CAR-T cells do not need to persist indefinitely. They need to do their job and clear.</p>
  <p>CRISPR Therapeutics' allogeneic candidate zugo-cel — formerly CTX112, targeting CD19 — is now in a Phase 1 basket trial enrolling patients with systemic lupus erythematosus, systemic sclerosis, and inflammatory myositis. As of December 2025, four patients had received zugo-cel at 100 million cells: two with SLE, two with immune-mediated necrotizing myopathy with interstitial lung disease. Rapid and deep B-cell depletion was observed within one to two days of infusion and maintained over the first month. The therapy was well tolerated, with cell expansion comparable to oncology trials.</p>
  <p>The allogeneic engineering is where CRISPR's specific contribution becomes visible. Zugo-cel's cells are CRISPR-edited to disrupt the T-cell receptor alpha chain (TRAC), preventing graft-versus-host disease from donor T cells. HLA-A, HLA-B, and CIITA are knocked out to reduce recognition and rejection by the host immune system. PD-1 disruption enhances CAR-T persistence and potency. These are not minor modifications — they are the difference between a therapy that requires a patient-specific manufacturing run and one that can be produced at scale from healthy donors and stored off the shelf.</p>
  <p>The TyU19 data, published in <em>Cell Research</em> in 2025, represents the first clinical application of allogeneic CRISPR-edited anti-CD19 CAR-T cells in refractory SLE patients. The cells carried the same five CRISPR disruptions — TRAC, HLA-A, HLA-B, CIITA, and PD-1 — and demonstrated significant clinical remission with a favorable safety profile. These are small numbers. The follow-up is short. But the signal is real, and the mechanistic logic is coherent in a way that the HIV excision strategy, for all its elegance, has not yet demonstrated in humans.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The hit-and-run strategy works precisely because it does not need to be permanent. That is not a limitation of the design. That is the design."</p></aside>

<section id="safety-architecture" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Safety Architecture Is Not Fully Built</h2>
  <p>The phrase "generally encouraging" appears in multiple characterizations of CRISPR's clinical safety profile. A careful reader should find that phrase unsettling, not reassuring. It is the language of a field that has not yet accumulated enough patient-years to know what it does not know.</p>
  <p>The AAV9 vectors used in EBT-101 persist in the body long after the editing event is complete. There is no off-switch. Once the Cas9 machinery is delivered, it continues to be expressed until the AAV episome degrades — a process that can take months to years in non-dividing cells. The cumulative risk of off-target cuts during that window is not zero, and it is not fully characterized. A 2025 review in <em>Life (MDPI)</em> identified off-target effects, immunogenicity, and delivery of the large CRISPR-Cas9 complex as unresolved challenges across HIV gene therapy strategies. These are not theoretical concerns. They are engineering problems that have not been solved.</p>
  <p>In autoimmune applications, the risk profile shifts but does not disappear. CRISPR-enhanced CAR-T cells in a patient whose immune system is already dysregulated carry cytokine release syndrome risk. The same inflammatory milieu that characterizes active lupus or systemic sclerosis is the milieu into which these cells are infused. Lymphodepletion conditioning — required before CAR-T infusion — adds its own toxicity burden. The zugo-cel trial's favorable tolerability data at one month is encouraging. One month is not a safety profile.</p>
  <p>The 2025 death of a patient with Duchenne muscular dystrophy in a CRISPR trial run by the nonprofit Cure Rare Disease is the field's most sobering recent data point. The specifics of that case — the patient's baseline condition, the exact mechanism of the adverse event — are still being analyzed. What it establishes is that CRISPR-related clinical deaths are no longer hypothetical. The field has crossed that threshold. That does not mean the technology is unsafe. It means the technology is in the phase of development where the real safety data is being generated, in real patients, in real time.</p>
  <p>Caribou Biosciences' decision to abandon its autoimmune CAR-T program entirely — driven by financial pressure rather than safety signals — illustrates a different kind of structural fragility. The companies developing these therapies are operating on venture timelines in a regulatory environment that requires decade-scale evidence. When the money runs out before the evidence accumulates, programs die regardless of their scientific merit. That is not a CRISPR problem. It is a biotech financing problem that CRISPR happens to be living inside.</p>
</section>

