<section id="what-the-mechanism-teaches" class="reveal">
  <h2>What the Mechanism Is Actually Teaching</h2>
  <p>The productive failure of EBT-101 has clarified something important about the relationship between editing efficiency and therapeutic outcome. In HIV, you need to reach essentially every latently infected cell — a number estimated in the millions, distributed across anatomical compartments with varying AAV9 accessibility. In autoimmune disease, you need to deplete a population of cells that is circulating, accessible, and does not need to be permanently eliminated. The therapeutic bar is different by orders of magnitude.</p>
  <p>This is not an argument that CRISPR cannot eventually work for HIV. The 2025 Ragon Institute data — 90% CCR5 editing efficiency in human hematopoietic stem cells, with protection maintained against five-times-dose HIV rechallenge in xenograft mice — represents a genuine advance in the protect strategy. The 2023 dual-CRISPR approach published in <em>Nature Communications</em>, combining CCR5 disruption with excision of an HIV DNA region essential for replication alongside LASER ART, eliminated HIV in over half of infected humanized mice with no off-target effects and no viral rebound. The mouse-to-human translation problem is real and persistent, but the mechanistic progress is not illusory.</p>
  <p>Lipid nanoparticle delivery — identified in the 2025 <em>Current Opinion in HIV and AIDS</em> review as a promising next step beyond AAV9 — may eventually solve the distribution problem that AAV9 cannot. LNPs can be engineered for tissue tropism, can be administered repeatedly without the immunogenicity ceiling that limits AAV re-dosing, and do not persist indefinitely in the way AAV episomes do. Whether they can achieve sufficient penetration into the gut-associated lymphoid tissue and CNS compartments where HIV reservoirs concentrate is an open question. It is the right question.</p>
  <p>Fyodor Urnov of the Innovative Genomics Institute at UC Berkeley has described gene editing as "the first-ever technology we have had to address disease at the DNA level." That framing is accurate and also incomplete. Addressing disease at the DNA level is necessary but not sufficient when the disease has evolved specifically to exploit the gap between what you can edit and what you need to edit. HIV has had 40 years of evolutionary pressure against every cure strategy humans have deployed. CRISPR is the most precise instrument yet brought to that fight. Precision is not the same as reach.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"Precision is not the same as reach. HIV has had 40 years of evolutionary pressure against every cure strategy humans have deployed. CRISPR is the most precise instrument yet brought to that fight — and the fight is not over."</p></aside>

<section id="the-equity-problem" class="reveal">
  <h2>Who Will It Work For</h2>
  <p>There are approximately 38 million people living with HIV globally. The majority are in sub-Saharan Africa. The HIV subtypes circulating in sub-Saharan Africa are not the subtypes that EBT-101's guide RNAs were designed against. The manufacturing infrastructure required to produce allogeneic CRISPR CAR-T therapies at clinical scale does not exist in sub-Saharan Africa. The regulatory pathways, the cold-chain logistics, the clinical monitoring infrastructure — none of it exists at the scale required to deliver a one-time gene therapy to the populations carrying the highest HIV burden on earth.</p>
  <p>This is not a future problem that better technology will eventually solve. It is baked into the current development model. CRISPR therapeutics are being developed by companies that answer to investors who require return on capital. The markets where that return is achievable are wealthy markets: the United States, Europe, Japan. The patients in those markets with HIV are, by and large, well-managed on antiretroviral therapy. They are not the patients for whom an HIV cure is most urgently needed. They are the patients for whom an HIV cure is most commercially viable.</p>
  <p>The autoimmune applications — lupus, systemic sclerosis, inflammatory myositis — affect patient populations that are disproportionately located in wealthier countries with functioning healthcare systems and insurance structures capable of absorbing the cost of a gene therapy. The first approved CRISPR therapy, Casgevy for sickle cell disease, carries a list price of $2.2 million per patient. There is no structural reason to expect CRISPR autoimmune therapies to be priced differently. There is every structural reason to expect them to be priced similarly or higher.</p>
  <p>The equity problem in CRISPR HIV therapy is not that the technology is being developed in the wrong places. It is that the incentive structure of pharmaceutical development systematically produces therapies for the patients most able to pay, not the patients most in need. That structure predates CRISPR and will outlast it. The question the field is not asking loudly enough — not in the trial registrations, not in the investor presentations, not in the conference abstracts — is the one that matters most: if CRISPR eventually works for HIV, who will it work for?</p>
  <p>The answer, under the current model, is not the 25 million people in sub-Saharan Africa who need it most. That is not a prediction about the technology. It is a description of the world the technology is being built inside.</p>
</section>

